snippet.textDisplay:
I'd love to see 120mm radial blowers make a comeback, I used that 80mm blower from CoolerMaster back in the day and it performed great on the DIY waterloop!

I had a small motorcycle radiator stuck to the back where the outtake fan is supposed to be and the blower just pumped out heat like crazy on a single core AMD MP 1600 clocked to 2100!

The radiator in the back was the only one with a fan, there were two passive radiators in drivebays at the front after it in the loop.

snippet.textDisplay: The cooler has an obvious issue. Thermosiphons in large installations involve taking the heat outside the box. The design you show is not optimal for that. No matter how good this cooler, unless you take the heat out of the machine it is still going to be inferior to proper water cooling. What do I mean by "proper water cooling"? I mean a custom loop. To be clear, my 2950X running prime 95 with 32 threads never goes above 36C @ 21C ambient. Even more important, the same loop cools both the CPU and a 2080Ti. As I know people will ask: TT D5, 560mm (60mm deep) radiator with push/pull. There is just over two litres of water in the system.
snippet.textOriginal: The cooler has an obvious issue. Thermosiphons in large installations involve taking the heat *outside* the box. The design you show is not optimal for that. No matter how good this cooler, unless you take the heat out of the machine it is still going to be inferior to proper water cooling. What do I mean by "proper water cooling"? I mean a custom loop. To be clear, my 2950X running prime 95 with 32 threads never goes above 36C @ 21C ambient. Even more important, the same loop cools both the CPU *and* a 2080Ti. As I know people will ask: TT D5, 560mm (60mm deep) radiator with push/pull. There is just over two litres of water in the system.
